   :chapter: 11-regex
   :subchapter: 11-glossary
   :topics: 11-regex/11-glossary
   :from_source: T
   :feedback: Look above for the definitions of these terms.
   :match_1: brittle code|||Code that works when the input data is in a particular format but is prone to breakage if there is some deviation from the correct format. We call this "brittle code" because it is easily broken.
   :match_2: greedy matching|||The notion that the ``+`` and ``*`` characters in a regular expression expand outward to match the largest possible string.
   :match_3: grep|||A command available in most Unix systems that searches through text files looking for lines that match regular expressions. The command name stands for "Generalized Regular Expression Parser".
   :match_4: regular expression|||A language for expressing more complex search strings. A regular expression may contain special characters that indicate that a search only matches at the beginning or end of a line or many other similar capabilities.
   :match_5: wild card|||A special character that matches any character. In regular expressions the wild-card character is the period.

   Match the following terms with their definitions.